This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with natural language processing tasks such as dialogue generation and intention recognition. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel neural network architecture for dialogue act classification, which is a common task in the field of computational linguistics. 

The paper also involves the use of deep learning techniques, which suggests that it could belong to the sub-categories of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). 

Furthermore, the paper involves the use of attention mechanisms, which are commonly used in the sub-category of cs.SD (Sound) for speech recognition tasks. 

Finally, the paper involves the use of neural networks to model the interactions between dialogue acts and topics, which suggests that it could belong to the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) for neural network modelling.
